AGI - Who promotes it tends to define it as a historical success of the European Union, as well as the joint purchase of vaccines against Covid and Next Generation Eu: the new pact for migration and asylum is aimed at facilitating the reception of asylum seekers and to encourage the return of those who do not have the right to remain in Europe. It reforms the current system of management of migratory policies that in recent years has consistently proved not to meet the challenges.
&nbsp;
The package includes nine legislative acts and will be voted tomorrow at the European Parliament for the final freeway. The Regulation on the management of asylum and migration is the main element and should replace the Dublin Regulation, which lays down rules for determining which Member State is competent for the examination of an application for asylum. To balance the current system, according to which few Member States of entry (including Italy) are responsible for the vast majority of asylum applications, provides for a new compulsory solidarity mechanism, as well as measures to prevent abuse and secondary movements.
&nbsp;
To help countries under severe migratory pressure, other Member States may choose to relocate asylum seekers in their territory or pay financial contributions. The calculation of the contribution of each Member State is based on the size of the population (50%) and its GDP (50%), while each country is free to decide the type of contribution or a combination of these. The new regulation, as agreed, sets the minimum threshold for relocations to 30 thousand applicants and the financial contribution to 600 million euros. In the event of insufficient relocation commitments, a beneficiary Member State may request the other Member States to assume responsibility for examining applications for international protection for persons who must be repatriated to the beneficiary Member State, instead of contributing with relocations. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
The second file is the Regulation on the asylum procedure which establishes a common procedure at EU level for the granting or revocation of international protection, replacing the different national procedures. It contains rules on the border procedure that allow rapid evaluation at external borders if applications are unfounded or inadmissible. The aim is to make asylum and repatriation procedures at the faster and more effective borders, up to 12 weeks. It will accelerate the processing of asylum applications (up to six months for a first decision) and provide shorter deadlines for manifestly unfounded or inadmissible applications and borders. Asylum applicants whose requests are rejected should be repatriated in less than 12 weeks.
&nbsp;
Persons considered a danger to national security or public order, or if the applicant deceived the authorities by submitting false information on identity or nationality, and those coming from countries with asylum recognition rates below 20% will always be subject to the border asylum procedure immediately after screening. Minors are excluded from the procedure unless they represent a safety hazard.
&nbsp;
Among other provisions, it is planned to create reception centers in the country of first entry. The appropriate capacity at EU level for border procedures will be 30 thousand places of welcome and the Member States must ensure that they are able to carry out border procedures on their territory. Each country will have a maximum number of questions (annual ceiling) to be examined in the border procedure, which will be determined by the Commission. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
There is also the Regulation on crisis situations. It establishes appropriate procedural rules, exceptions and the rapid activation of solidarity mechanisms to respond to crisis situations, such as that occurred in 2015 and 2016, when more than two million people arrived in the EU. It provides for a mechanism of solidarity and measures to support Member States facing an exceptional influx of third-country nationals leading to the saturation of the national asylum regime. In the face of a crisis, the Member State concerned will have to submit a reasoned request to the Commission, which will assess the situation within two weeks and take a decision on whether or not a crisis situation. It will also submit a proposal to the Council on measures of solidarity and derogations, together with a recommendation establishing the categories of persons who should have the right to first-time protection. The rules also aim to counter the exploitation of migrants, i.e. the situation in which non-State hostile countries or actors use migrants to destabilize the EU, and provide a possible temporary derogation from standard asylum procedures.
&nbsp;
<h2> Reformation Eurodac</h2>
It will allow you to identify more effectively who arrives on the EU territory, adding images of the face to fingerprints, and will concern children from six years (to protect them and make more simply possible reunion with family members). Authorities may record those who pose a threat to security, or when the person is violent or irregular. A common database will collect more accurate and complete information to detect unauthorized movements. Screening regulations.
&nbsp;
The aim is to create uniform standards for the identification of third-country nationals upon arrival, thereby increasing safety within the Schengen area. Persons who do not meet the requirements to enter the EU will be subject to a pre-entry screening procedure, which will include identification, collection of biometric data and health and safety controls, for a maximum duration of seven days. The specific needs of children will be taken into account and each country will have an independent monitoring mechanism to ensure respect for fundamental rights. The Covenant also includes the Regulation of the European Agency for Asylum, as well as &nbsp; standards for harmonizing the protection and rights of asylum seekers in the Member States, new rules for improving the reception conditions of international protection applicants and a new framework for the adoption of a resettlement plan. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;

