AGI -&nbsp;&nbsp;The European Court of Human Rights has condemned Switzerland for violation of the Convention of Human Rights, giving reason to an association of older women who attacked the federal inaction against the fight against climate change. It is the first time that the Court, which watches over the respect of the Convention, condemns a State for its lack of initiative against climate change.
&nbsp;
Switzerland will have to pay the association €80,000 for legal fees. The decision of the ECHR is definitive and Switzerland will have the obligation to respect it and therefore to double the efforts in the fight against climate change. "This detailed decision will be analysed with the authorities concerned and the measures that Switzerland will take for the future will be examined," said the federal government. Alain Chablais, representative of the Swiss government in front of the ECHR, explained that "the means (to be implemented) will be determined by the Swiss government and parliament" and that it will take "a certain time to determine what measures will be taken". The Committee of Ministers of the Council of Europe will subsequently verify the conformity of Switzerland with the judgment. "We will be extremely careful to ensure that Switzerland implements the decision," said Anne Mahrer, one of the environmental activists who condemned Bern.
&nbsp;
The judgment is a precedent, in the sense that it could serve as reference in other cases related to climate change. In fact, the measure will also apply to the 46 Member States of the Council of Europe. In fact, in the judgment, the ECHR explains that the national authorities have a "margin of appreciation" and can choose the measures to be implemented to achieve their objectives. A State must therefore have precise objectives in terms of reducing greenhouse gases, a carbon budget or any other equivalent method to quantify future greenhouse gas emissions, and a monitoring mechanism to verify that these objectives are achieved.
&nbsp;
"The Court has established a list of requirements for a state to comply with its climate obligations and this is completely new," said Raphael Mahaim, one of the lawyers of the Swiss Climate Elders Association. "There are great hopes that things will move quickly enough."
&nbsp;
"This is only the beginning in terms of climate dispute: worldwide, more and more people bring their governments to court to hold them responsible for their actions," said Swedish activist Greta Thunberg, present in Strasbourg for the decision.
&nbsp;
In Italy
In Italy only a few weeks ago the use of the Universal Judgement Campaign was rejected, which collected about 200 subjects. The judges held the case against the Italian state's inaction on the climate crisis and the reduction of emissions by default. Activists promise to appeal against the first degree pronunciation.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Throughout the world, the climate causes brought by associations are about 2500 and aim to nail the States to their responsibilities regarding decarbonization and lowering of emissions.&nbsp;

